British doctors in Scotland measured telomere length in middle-aged men to identify those at risk of heart disease.
Statin treatment reduced heart disease risk for men with short telomeres.
A gene variant in women increases susceptibility to heart disease.
Gum disease may be linked to pancreatic cancer.
The heart peptide test is a predictor of heart disease severity.
Congenital heart disease prevalence is rising in adults and children.
Statins may protect against heart disease by limiting telomere damage.
Childhood trauma increases the risk of heart disease in adulthood.
Air pollution increases the risk of cardiovascular disease in postmenopausal women.
